Analyses on Fuel-Related Aircraft Accidents¶

This project seeks to identify the factors most relevant to fuel-related aircraft accidents. In doing so, models will be created to predict if an accident is fuel-related based on a collection of features.

Initial Setup¶

PySpark and Pandas will be used for the bulk of the project. However, there is no way to open the Microsoft Access file in either. 'pyodbc' is a module that enables the use of the .mdb file the data is in. \ \ There is no way to convert directly from pyodbc to PySpark, so Pandas will be used as an intermediate stage where the querying of the database will also occur.

Queries and Conversion to Pandas

The 'Findings' table contains codes that describe the problems that occurred in the accidents. However, the table splits each event into multiple occurrences. As a result, each value in the event ID variable, 'ev_id,' is duplicated. This project seeks to look at aircraft accidents as single events. \ \ Therefore, the 'Findings' table will be queried separately, relevant data related to fuel and engines will be identified, and that information will be merged with the main dataset to prevent duplication. As the 'narr_cause' variable from the 'narratives' table also contains data pertinent to this, it will be included in the query as well.

In [4]:
# Queries

query1 = '''SELECT DISTINCT aircraft.ev_id, aircraft.acft_category, events.ev_date, aircraft.acft_make,
           aircraft.acft_model, events.ev_type, events.ev_state, events.ev_country, events.latitude, events.longitude, 
           events.ev_highest_injury, events.inj_tot_t, engines.eng_type, engines.eng_mfgr, engines.eng_model,
           engines.power_units, engines.hp_or_lbs, engines.carb_fuel_injection, aircraft.far_part, aircraft.damage,
           aircraft.acft_fire, aircraft.acft_expl, aircraft.num_eng, aircraft.type_fly, aircraft.site_seeing, 
           aircraft.acft_year, events.apt_dist, events.light_cond, events.wx_temp, events.wind_vel_kts,
           aircraft.cert_max_gr_wt, aircraft.homebuilt, aircraft.afm_hrs, aircraft.afm_hrs_last_insp, narratives.narr_cause
           
           FROM (events INNER JOIN (((((aircraft LEFT JOIN dt_aircraft ON (aircraft.Aircraft_Key = dt_aircraft.Aircraft_Key)
           AND (aircraft.ev_id = dt_aircraft.ev_id)) LEFT JOIN engines ON (aircraft.Aircraft_Key = engines.Aircraft_Key)
           AND (aircraft.ev_id = engines.ev_id)) LEFT JOIN Events_Sequence ON (aircraft.Aircraft_Key = 
           Events_Sequence.Aircraft_Key) AND (aircraft.ev_id = Events_Sequence.ev_id)) LEFT JOIN Findings ON
           (aircraft.Aircraft_Key = Findings.Aircraft_Key) AND (aircraft.ev_id = Findings.ev_id)) LEFT JOIN narratives ON
           (aircraft.Aircraft_Key = narratives.Aircraft_Key) AND (aircraft.ev_id = narratives.ev_id)) ON events.ev_id =
           aircraft.ev_id) LEFT JOIN dt_events ON events.ev_id = dt_events.ev_id'''

query2 = '''SELECT DISTINCT Findings.ev_id, Findings.finding_description, Findings.finding_code, Findings.category_no,
            Findings.subcategory_no, Findings.section_no, Findings.subsection_no, Findings.modifier_no, Findings.Cause_Factor,
            narratives.narr_cause
            
            FROM Findings LEFT JOIN narratives ON (Findings.ev_id = narratives.ev_id)'''

Creating New Variables¶

There are several variables that must be created, as they are essential for visualization and modeling.

Variable Description </b> Example(s)
1 fuel_rel Identifies if an event is fuel-related based on codes 0, 1
2 eng_rel Identifies if an event is engine-related (contains 'fuel_rel') 0, 1
3 fuel_narr Identifies if the word 'fuel' is mentioned in the 'narr_cause' variable 0, 1
4 fuel_rel_cf Identifies if any part of the code-based 'fuel_rel' was a cause or factor 0, 1
5 eng_rel_cf Identifies if any part of the code-based 'eng_rel' was a cause or factor 0, 1
6 fuel_narr_cf Identifies if any part of the search-based 'fuel_narr' was a cause or factor 0, 1
7 target Identifies if the event contains a target aircraft/engine 0, 1
8 target_mfgr Identifies the manufacturer the target belongs to HAWKER, CESSNA, PIPER, NO

Ultimately, 'fuel_rel' and 'eng_rel' will be dependent variables in modeling, but each will be relevant in data exploration and analysis.

In [9]:
from pyspark.sql import functions as F
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, isnan, when, count, asc, desc, rpad, rank, sum, lit, trim
from pyspark.ml.feature import Imputer

The variables 'fuel_rel' and 'eng_rel' will be developed using the relevant codes in 'finding_code.' \ \ There could be multiple different fuel-related occurrences in an event, or there could be non-fuel-related occurrences in the sequence of an event. If the latter exists, the existence of '0' and '1' values in variable creation will cause duplications of the 'ev_id' variable, which would then cause duplications in joining with the main dataset. Therefore, only '1' values will be added. By separating the variables from the rest in the dataframe, using the 'distinct' and 'na.drop' functions would effectively cause only unique 'ev_id' values to remain as well as the indication set by 'fuel_rel' and 'eng_rel.' '0' values will be added after the join.

In [10]:
AVFIND = AVFIND.withColumn('fuel_rel', 
     when(AVFIND.finding_code.contains('010228'), '1') #aircraft systems - fuel system
    .when(AVFIND.finding_code.contains('010573'), '1') #engine fuel and control                    
    .when(AVFIND.finding_code.contains('01071010'), '1') #fluids/misc hardware - fuel
    .when(AVFIND.finding_code.contains('01071040'), '1') #fluids/misc hardware - fuel additive                    
    )
In [11]:
AVFIND = AVFIND.withColumn('eng_rel', 
     when(AVFIND.fuel_rel == '1', '1') #including fuel-related issues
    .when(AVFIND.finding_code.contains('0105'), '1') #aircraft power plant                   
    .when(AVFIND.finding_code.contains('0107102'), '1') #fluids/misc hardware - oil & coolant
    .when(AVFIND.finding_code.contains('01071045'), '1') #fluids/misc hardware - oil additive                       
    )

Next, the 'fuel_narr' variable will be created. It will check mentions of the word 'fuel' in 'narr_cause' and include accidents tracked by the 'fuel_rel' variable. This way, values of '1' in 'fuel_narr' but not 'fuel_rel' will indicate situations where a problem involving fuel occurred, but they would not be ones tracked by the 'fuel_rel' variable's codes. These may be issues caused by human negligence or some other factor not tracked by the finding codes. Similar to the 'fuel_rel' and 'eng_rel' variables, there will be no '0' values for now.

In [12]:
AVFIND = AVFIND.withColumn('fuel_narr',
     when(AVFIND.narr_cause.contains('fuel'), '1')
    .when(AVFIND.fuel_rel == '1', '1')                                        
    )

A similar approach is taken with the 'Cause_Factor' variable. Each observation that has a value of '1' in 'fuel_rel,' 'eng_rel,' and 'fuel_narr' and a 'C' in 'Cause_Factor' (which indicates the occurrence was a cause of the event) receives a '1' value, and the '0' will be imputed after the join

In [13]:
AVFIND = AVFIND.withColumn('fuel_rel_cf',
     when((AVFIND.fuel_rel == '1') & (AVFIND.Cause_Factor == 'C'), '1'))

AVFIND = AVFIND.withColumn('eng_rel_cf',
     when((AVFIND.eng_rel == '1') & (AVFIND.Cause_Factor == 'C'), '1'))

AVFIND = AVFIND.withColumn('fuel_narr_cf',
     when((AVFIND.fuel_narr == '1') & (AVFIND.Cause_Factor == 'C'), '1'))

Distinct values are kept and observations with null values are dropped. Due to how we handled the new variables, each of the new dataframes should have unique values in 'ev_id' with no duplicates.

Expanding 'fuel_rel' into 'eng_rel' almost doubles the number of relevant events. Therefore, the number of fuel-related issues and engine-related issues is about the same. The broadening with 'eng_rel' could help with training in a predictive model as there are more observations in the minority classification, but it could also lead to weaker models as the classification is less focused. Regardless, the imbalance in both variables would need to be addressed in modeling. Further understandings of these dependent variables will be learned through their use in analyzing other variables. \ \ Next, we will examine the frequencies at which the causes of events were fuel-related and engine-related.

These results indicate that a finding being considered a cause does not mean that it was the starting issue. Causes may instead mean significant problem points that directly lead to the accidents. Minor affairs in an overarching accident event may not have the severity to be considered causes, only factors. \ \ To further understand the types of fuel-related accidents, we can look at each occurrence and how they are classified. 'fuel_narr' from the findings dataframe, 'AVFIND,' will be looked at, as it is the variable that encompasses the widest variety of fuel-related data by including the codes represented in 'fuel_rel' and observations with mentions of 'fuel' in 'narr_cause.'

Aircraft issues only account for 50% of all the fuel-based findings in every event. Even within the 50%, many of those technical problems were caused by personnel issues leading to fuel exhaustion. Adjusting the data to remove all instances of problems caused by fuel exhaustion would be a monumental task, and there may not even be enough data remaining to build an effective model. As a result, using 'fuel_rel' and 'eng_rel' as dependent variables would likely lead to predicting for fuel exhaustion. There may be benefits to that, however, as there may be some variable values that may be correlated with aircraft suffering from that complication.

Numeric Variables

Binary Variables

Before looking at the numeric features, there are several categorical variables that can be transformed into binary numeric variables. This will help with modeling, as the 'scikit-learn' package that will be used for modeling requires that features only contain values of '0' and '1'. While dummy variables can be created for both of these variables' values, making the values '0' and '1' ahead of time will reduce the number of features in modeling, making modeling easier. \ \ For example, 'ev_type,' which only has the values 'INC' and 'ACC,' would become 'ev_type_INC' and 'ev_type_ACC' when converted into dummies when it can just remain 'ev_type' if 'INC' and 'ACC' are turned into '0' and '1.' The below table contains the variables that will be adjusted in this way.

Variable Description </b> Values to Become 0, 1
1 ev_type Type of event (classified by severity; accident is more serious) INC, ACC
2 site_seeing Indicates if aircraft was conducting siteseeing operations N, Y
3 homebuilt Indicates if aircraft is amateur-built N, Y
4 hp_or_lbs Indicates engine power unit of measure HP, LBS
5 carb_fuel_injection For aircraft with reciprocating engines, indicates the fuel system (carburetor or fuel-injected) CARB, FINJ
In [28]:
AVGAS = AVGAS.withColumn('ev_type',
     when(AVGAS.ev_type == 'INC', '0')
    .when(AVGAS.ev_type == 'ACC', '1'))

AVGAS = AVGAS.withColumn('site_seeing',
     when(AVGAS.site_seeing == 'N', '0')
    .when(AVGAS.site_seeing == 'Y', '1'))

AVGAS = AVGAS.withColumn('homebuilt',
     when(AVGAS.homebuilt == 'N', '0')
    .when(AVGAS.homebuilt == 'Y', '1'))

AVGAS = AVGAS.withColumn('hp_or_lbs',
     when(AVGAS.hp_or_lbs == 'HP', '0')
    .when(AVGAS.hp_or_lbs == 'LBS', '1'))

AVGAS = AVGAS.withColumn('carb_fuel_injection',
     when(AVGAS.carb_fuel_injection == 'CARB', '0')
    .when(AVGAS.carb_fuel_injection == 'FINJ', '1'))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

def draw_histograms(dataframe, features, rows, cols):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))
    for i, feature in enumerate(features):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(rows,cols,i+1)
        dataframe[feature].hist(bins = 3, ax = ax, facecolor = 'blue')
        ax.set_title(feature + " Distribution", color='red')       
    fig.tight_layout()  
    plt.show()
    
draw_histograms(AVGAS_binary.toPandas(), AVGAS_binary.toPandas().columns, 7, 3)

All of the binary variables are imbalanced. The number of target aircraft is very small relative to every aircraft. The target is meant to be a very small portion of overall aircraft for initial testing, so this makes sense. Almost all of the event types are accidents and not incidents, indicating that nearly all aircraft suffered damage or an amount of people were injured. While 'site_seeing' could have been interesting in indicating a type of flight, it appears nearly useless. Most aircraft are not homebuilt, but over 2,000 of about 17,000 are. The engine power for most aircraft is recorded in horsepower. While still imbalanced, 'carb_fuel_injection' is the most balanced of the above variables, but there are more fuel systems with carburetor rather than fuel injection.

def draw_histograms(dataframe, features, rows, cols):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))
    for i, feature in enumerate(features):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(rows,cols,i+1)
        dataframe[feature].hist(bins = 10, ax = ax, facecolor = 'blue')
        ax.set_title(feature + " Distribution", color='red')       
    fig.tight_layout()  
    plt.show()

draw_histograms(AVGAS_contin.toPandas(), AVGAS_contin.toPandas().columns, 7, 3)

It appears as though all the variables have a huge positive skew. However, there are values that are so high that the binning for the bars is not very effective. This may be an indication of outliers so they will be identified and addressed.

Dictionaries are set and filled with values related to outlier detection for easier math in Python.

In [36]:
quarters = dict()
iqr = dict()
lower = dict()
upper = dict()
lower_out = dict()
upper_out = dict()
total_out = dict()

for column in AVGAS_contin.columns:
    quarters[column] = AVGAS.approxQuantile(column, [0.25, 0.5, 0.75], 0)
    iqr[column] = quarters[column][2] - quarters[column][0]
    lower[column] = quarters[column][0] - (1.5 * iqr[column])
    upper[column] = quarters[column][2] + (1.5 * iqr[column])
    lower_out[column] = (AVGAS.filter(col(column) < lower[column])).count()
    upper_out[column] = (AVGAS.filter(col(column) > upper[column])).count()
    total_out[column] = lower_out[column] + upper_out[column]

'power_units' Exploration

The variable 'power_units' has a significant issue. It measures engine output power, but the values use two separate units of measure: horsepower (HP) and pounds of thrust (LBS), which is tracked by the 'hp_or_lbs' variable. It's not possible to convert one into the other as the velocity of the aircraft is required (the conversion equation is LBS * V / 375 = HP). Values of 'power_units' where 'hp_or_lbs' is '1' will be removed.

In [63]:
print('Values removed:', AVGAS.filter(col('hp_or_lbs') == 1).count())

AVGAS = AVGAS.withColumn('power_units', when(AVGAS.hp_or_lbs != 1, col('power_units')))

Values removed: 542

As 'hp_or_lbs' was imputed with '0' (for HP), there could be values that are still in lbs, as there could have been values for 'power_units' where 'hp_or_lbs' is null. The highest values will be examined, as values for lbs tend to be higher than HP.

    for i, feature in enumerate(features):

There are several key observations made from this visualization and its largest words. First, the word 'pilot' is among the largest. Typically, the pilot is mentioned in the narrative cause when the pilot made some type of error or the problem was due to negligence. The word 'loss' and the phrase 'engine power' go hand-in-hand; the phrase 'loss of engine power' appears frequently in fuel-related accidents, indicating that these types of issues typically cause the engine to stop working. The words 'exhaustion' and 'starvation' also stick out, and these represent different types of fuel difficulties in aircraft.

Predictive Modeling¶

Predictive modeling will be done using the 'scikit-learn' package in Python. Three different predictive models will be developed for each dependent variable: a decision tree, a logistic regression, and a random forest. The decision tree and logistic regression can be compared as different simple models, while the decision tree and random forest can be compared as a simple and complex version of the same core idea.
